dasovich-j_all_documents_8956.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 38 @@@ 77 @@@ proved in the famous experiment wherein benjamin franklin flew a kite during

giron-d_inbox_310.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 5 @@@ 782 @@@ all metro passes offered through the enron parking transportation desk will be the metro 30 day zone pass when you use a 30 day zone pass bus service is divided into four zones w unlimited rides the zone pass is time activated which means that it will not become active until the first time it is used and will not expire until 30 days after it was used for the first time new passes will be available to enron employees upon expiration of the 30 day time period each zone does have a different fare values based on the distance the bus travels this is important to any buser who wants to transfer to or travel in a higher cost zone than the zone pass they have in this case the difference must be paid in cash if they are traveling in a lower cost zone then there is no extra cost

haedicke-m_inbox_701.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 144 @@@ 74 @@@ ially creates is an information advantage for buyers who have six hours t 
haedicke-m_inbox_701.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 145 @@@ 75 @@@ o evaluate and respond to the incremental bids from some sellers some of t

haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 1 @@@ 76 @@@ as promised here is a cliff s notes version of the law of quantum meruit in 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 2 @@@ 19 @@@ the state of texas 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 4 @@@ 74 @@@ the doctrine of quantum meruit is based on the principle of equity that a 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 5 @@@ 76 @@@ party deserves to be paid for the services or materials he furnishes to one 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 6 @@@ 65 @@@ who knowingly accepts them see davidson v clearman 391 s w 2d 48 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 7 @@@ 72 @@@  tex 1965 this remedy is based on the promise implied by law to pay for 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 8 @@@ 73 @@@ beneficial services rendered and accepted id see campbell v northwestern 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 9 @@@ 70 @@@ nat l life ins co 573 s w 2d 496 498 tex 1978 the texas supreme court 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 10 @@@ 68 @@@ in bashara v baptist mem l hosp sys 685 s w 2d 307 tex 1985 set out 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 11 @@@ 68 @@@ four elements for recovery under quantum meruit 1 valuable services 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 12 @@@ 72 @@@ rendered or materials furnished 2 for the person sought to be charged 3 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 13 @@@ 73 @@@ which were accepted by the person sought to be charged and were used and 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 14 @@@ 72 @@@ enjoyed by him 4 under such circumstances that he would reasonably know 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 15 @@@ 74 @@@ that the plaintiff expected to be paid for the services bashara v baptist 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 16 @@@ 69 @@@ mem l hosp sys 685 s w 2d at 310 quoting city of ingleside v stewart 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 17 @@@ 68 @@@ 554 s w 2d 939 943 tex civ app corpus christi 1977 writ ref d n r e 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 19 @@@ 64 @@@ there are several cases all outside the state of texas in which 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 20 @@@ 76 @@@ recruiting agencies seek recovery under the doctrine of quantum meruit from 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 21 @@@ 72 @@@ companies with whom they have placed an individual cutting to the chase 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 22 @@@ 75 @@@ the fundamental inquiry in such a case have the elements of quantum meruit 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 23 @@@ 72 @@@ been satisfied ends up being a factual issue for a jury to decide not a 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 24 @@@ 27 @@@ legal question for a judge 
haedicke-m_notes_inbox_1101.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 26 @@@ 46 @@@ let me know if i can be of further assistance

scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 15 @@@ 22 @@@ wednesday june 13 2001
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 18 @@@ 37 @@@ federal panel may extend price limits
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 19 @@@ 102 @@@  utilities regulatory commission weighs expanding the plan beyond emergencies and throughout the west 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 22 @@@ 45 @@@ by ricardo alonso zaldivar times staff writer
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 24 @@@ 260 @@@  washington the federal energy regulatory commission responding to pressure from lawmakers state officials and consumers is considering a significant expansion of its plan to limit california electricity prices this summer senior agency officials said tuesday 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 25 @@@ 162 @@@  commissioners and staff members are engaged in intense negotiations in advance of a key meeting monday to finalize an emergency plan for california and the west 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 26 @@@ 79 @@@  according to several commission officials the options being discussed include 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 27 @@@ 359 @@@  extending ferc s current price limits now in effect only during power emergencies in california to 24 hours a day seven days a week the limits intended to prevent price spikes were invoked during two emergencies last month and resulted in immediate cuts in the price of wholesale electricity ferc is also considering applying such limits throughout the west 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 28 @@@ 185 @@@  requiring power generators in the entire western region to sell available electricity to california or into their local power grids during emergencies reducing the threat of blackouts 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 29 @@@ 267 @@@  establishing a regional framework for large power users to sell electricity back into the grid during peak usage times some companies that have long term power contracts at low rates may be able to make money by scaling back their operations and selling electricity 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 30 @@@ 154 @@@  tightening rules on what energy marketers firms that buy and resell power contracts much like stockbrokers trade shares can charge for their electricity 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 31 @@@ 208 @@@  expanding an order issued last year that authorized refunds for excessive markups during the most extreme power emergencies that refund order would now apply to excessive prices during all power emergencies 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 32 @@@ 182 @@@  the measures under consideration stop short of the price caps being sought by gov gray davis and california democrats but they may go far enough to provide an acceptable compromise 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 33 @@@ 161 @@@  the whole thing is in flux but it is moving toward a much more effective price mitigation plan not only for california but for the west said an agency official 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 34 @@@ 187 @@@  strong political pressure from senate democrats and house republicans appears to have galvanized ferc into taking a more decisive role we re sort of the last to get it the official said 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 35 @@@ 177 @@@  ferc has been bitterly criticized by davis for abandoning california ferc chairman curtis l hebert jr has responded by citing dozens of modest ferc actions to assist the state 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 36 @@@ 252 @@@  but hebert has resisted davis central demand that ferc use its legal authority to order a temporary return to fixed electricity rates such fixed rates based on the cost of producing power plus an allowance for profit were standard before deregulation 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 37 @@@ 299 @@@  the politics of the situation have changed significantly and commissioners are not immune to politics said another senior agency official the message from capitol hill has gotten stronger with a democratic senate even the bush administration is saying we should make sure there is no price gouging 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 38 @@@ 323 @@@  ferc members have been summoned to testify before the senate governmental affairs committee chaired by sen joseph i lieberman d conn a week from today meanwhile sen jeff bingaman d n m the new senate energy committee chairman has told ferc he will move legislation to cap electricity rates in the west unless it acts soon 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 39 @@@ 90 @@@  agency officials said commissioners do not want to face lieberman next week empty handed 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 40 @@@ 176 @@@  house republicans have also been prodding the agency on tuesday energy committee chairman w j billy tauzin r la wrote hebert to urge western wide round the clock price limits 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 41 @@@ 260 @@@  we strongly urge the commission to implement a comprehensive plan to mitigate wholesale prices and aggressively monitor wholesale sales of electric energy within the entire western systems coordinating council wrote tauzin referring to the western power grid 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 42 @@@ 219 @@@  ferc officials said a strong effort is underway to achieve a consensus on the five member commission lately riven by ideology but now bolstered by two new pragmatic commissioners who favor active oversight of industry 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 43 @@@ 242 @@@  commissioner william massey who for months has been a lonely dissenter is continuing to press for the traditional price caps sought by davis officials said once marginalized massey apparently is now being actively wooed by the other members 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 44 @@@ 218 @@@  s david freeman an energy advisor to gov davis said tuesday that expanding ferc s current price limits would be a positive step but he added that the governor continues to advocate a return to traditional fixed rates 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 45 @@@ 117 @@@  any strengthening of the ferc plan is in the public interest freeman told reporters at a washington news conference 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 46 @@@ 82 @@@  ferc s price limits are not keyed to a particular dollar amount but are flexible 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 47 @@@ 309 @@@  when a power emergency is called by the state ferc s plan limits the price that generators can charge to what it costs to produce power at the least efficient plant running at that time the costs of all the plants are determined beforehand by california s grid operator based on data filed by the generators 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 48 @@@ 148 @@@  another requirement of the ferc plan forces generators using the california grid to sell any power they have available during emergency conditions 
scholtes-d_ferc_42.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 49 @@@ 264 @@@  when the price limits were tested in two emergencies late last month prices came down quickly but power sellers complained that the limits were too strict and by the second emergency there was evidence that some sellers had started finding ways around the limits

whalley-l_notes_inbox_227.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 11 @@@ 72 @@@ below is a press release we distributed today that details a proposal we
whalley-l_notes_inbox_227.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 12 @@@ 70 @@@ have made to san diego gas electric to manage their entire electricity
whalley-l_notes_inbox_227.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 13 @@@ 66 @@@ load up to 3 300 megawatts for five years at a fixed price of 60 a
whalley-l_notes_inbox_227.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 14 @@@ 70 @@@ megawatt hour the proposal was detailed in our comments to the federal
whalley-l_notes_inbox_227.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 15 @@@ 66 @@@ energy regulatory commission on their recent proposed solutions to
whalley-l_notes_inbox_227.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 16 @@@ 10 @@@ caifornia 
whalley-l_notes_inbox_227.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 18 @@@ 70 @@@ as the release indicates forward contracting for electricity is a very
whalley-l_notes_inbox_227.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 19 @@@ 71 @@@ effective way for the state s utilities to manage the volitility in the
whalley-l_notes_inbox_227.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 20 @@@ 70 @@@ state s electricity markets with natural gas prices more than doubling
whalley-l_notes_inbox_227.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 21 @@@ 75 @@@ since last year and last week being up to seven times higher than last year
whalley-l_notes_inbox_227.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 22 @@@ 69 @@@ on the spot market up to 19 a million btu vs an average of about 2 50
whalley-l_notes_inbox_227.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 23 @@@ 70 @@@ in 1999 we feel that its imperative for utilities to take advantage of
whalley-l_notes_inbox_227.txt.ann @@@ Body @@@ 24 @@@ 68 @@@ these contracts so they can manage their own risk exposure and their

train_1088.ann @@@ Body @@@ 46 @@@ 66 @@@  sizeable data store people often run with at least 4g often 8g or
train_1088.ann @@@ Body @@@ 47 @@@ 59 @@@  more if you facet or group or sort on fields that are not

train_1088.ann @@@ Body @@@ 51 @@@ 65 @@@  i guess my point is that you shouldn t be surprised if 1g is too
train_1088.ann @@@ Body @@@ 52 @@@ 64 @@@  small i d start with 4 8g and then reduce it after you get some
train_1088.ann @@@ Body @@@ 53 @@@ 63 @@@  experience with your data and queries and now much memory they

train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 5 @@@ 66 @@@ well historically during the really old days optimize made a major
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 6 @@@ 63 @@@ difference as lucene evolved that difference was smaller and in
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 7 @@@ 59 @@@ recent anecdotal reports it s up to 10 improvement in query
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 8 @@@ 67 @@@ processing with the usual caveats that there are a ton of variables
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 9 @@@ 65 @@@ here including and especially how frequently the index is updated
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 10 @@@ 67 @@@ so since yours is rarely updated take that number with a huge grain
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 11 @@@ 67 @@@ of salt it s an open question whether a 10 increase assuming that s
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 12 @@@ 66 @@@ what you get is noticeable i mean if your query latency is 250 ms 
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 13 @@@ 66 @@@ who s going to notice if it s 10 seconds that s a different story 
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 15 @@@ 67 @@@ there s a subtext here about whether your query load is enough that
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 16 @@@ 67 @@@ a 10 improvement can ripple but that s only under pretty high query
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 17 @@@ 6 @@@ loads 
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 19 @@@ 5 @@@ best 
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 20 @@@ 5 @@@ erick
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 23 @@@ 83 @@@  we index rarely and in bulk as we re an organisation that deals in enabling access
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 24 @@@ 36 @@@ to leaked documents for journalists 
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 26 @@@ 83 @@@  the indexes are mostly static for 99 of the year we only optimise after reindexing
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 27 @@@ 29 @@@ due to schema changes or when
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 28 @@@ 20 @@@  we have a new leak 
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 30 @@@ 84 @@@  our workflow is to index on a staging server optimise then trigger replication to a
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 31 @@@ 37 @@@ production instance of solr we cannot
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 32 @@@ 84 @@@  index straight to production as extracting text from documents is expensive lots of
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 33 @@@ 40 @@@ ec2 machines running extract and we need
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 34 @@@ 85 @@@  to really hammer the solr server with updates up to 250 concurrent update request at
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 35 @@@ 11 @@@ some times 
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 37 @@@ 81 @@@  i ve never done benchmark tests but it s an interesting question i always worked
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 38 @@@ 38 @@@ on the assumption that if the optimise
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 39 @@@ 86 @@@  operation exists then there must be a reason also something tells me that having your
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 40 @@@ 39 @@@ index spread over 70 files must be bad 
train_1350.ann @@@ Body @@@ 42 @@@ 89 @@@  the oom error is certainly due to something else as it happens when we try indexing text

train_1613.ann @@@ Body @@@ 18 @@@ 39 @@@ are probably using the implicit router 
train_1613.ann @@@ Body @@@ 20 @@@ 67 @@@ the implicit router basically means that there is no shard routing 
train_1613.ann @@@ Body @@@ 21 @@@ 68 @@@ documents would be either indexed by the shard that received them or
train_1613.ann @@@ Body @@@ 22 @@@ 67 @@@ directed to the shard indicated by explicit routing parameters with
train_1613.ann @@@ Body @@@ 23 @@@ 67 @@@ three shards and distrib false requests to one shard you should see
train_1613.ann @@@ Body @@@ 24 @@@ 73 @@@ about one third of your total document count not the full document count 
train_1613.ann @@@ Body @@@ 26 @@@ 68 @@@ the router that you typically want if you don t want to be concerned
train_1613.ann @@@ Body @@@ 27 @@@ 69 @@@ about how documents are routed to different shards is the compositeid
train_1613.ann @@@ Body @@@ 28 @@@ 65 @@@ router this should be the default for a multi shard collection in

train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 87 @@@ 64 @@@  i ve heard that csv import runs extremely fast but i have never
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 88 @@@ 64 @@@  tested it the same threading problem that i discuss below would
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 89 @@@ 28 @@@  apply to indexing this way 
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 91 @@@ 62 @@@  dih is extremely powerful but it has one glaring problem it s
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 92 @@@ 66 @@@  single threaded which means that only one stream of data is going
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 93 @@@ 67 @@@  into solr and each batch of documents to be inserted must wait for
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 94 @@@ 66 @@@  the previous one to finish inserting before it can start i do not

train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 96 @@@ 63 @@@  have a manually sharded index you can run dih on each shard in
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 97 @@@ 68 @@@  parallel but each one will be single threaded that single thread is
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 98 @@@ 49 @@@  pretty efficient but it s still only one thread 
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 100 @@@ 68 @@@  sending multiple index updates to solr in parallel multi threading 
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 101 @@@ 64 @@@  is how you radically speed up the solr part of indexing this is
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 102 @@@ 67 @@@  usually done with a custom indexing program which might be written
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 103 @@@ 55 @@@  with solrj or even in a completely different language 
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 105 @@@ 60 @@@  one thing to keep in mind with any indexing method once the
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 106 @@@ 66 @@@  situation is examined closely most people find that it s not solr
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 107 @@@ 68 @@@  that makes their indexing slow the bottleneck is usually the source
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 108 @@@ 64 @@@  system how quickly the data can be retrieved it usually takes a
train_1837.ann @@@ Body @@@ 109 @@@ 65 @@@  lot longer to obtain the data than it does for solr to index it

train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 19 @@@ 67 @@@ the project is particularly interested in making sure that bugs are
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 20 @@@ 68 @@@ found and fixed quickly but each minor release will also include new
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 21 @@@ 62 @@@ features as well if a nasty bug is found a buxfix release will
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 22 @@@ 45 @@@ usually follow within the same minor release 
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 24 @@@ 65 @@@ major releases are less frequent but follow a similar pattern the
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 25 @@@ 70 @@@ next major release is developed in an entirely different branch of the
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 26 @@@ 70 @@@ source repository named master and it takes quite a lot of work to get
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 27 @@@ 64 @@@ that branch ready for release and make sure it works as desired 
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 29 @@@ 70 @@@ like alessandro mentioned we do recommend that you try to stay current
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 30 @@@ 67 @@@ in your solr install if you let your install get far enough behind 
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 31 @@@ 69 @@@ you ll probably find that many new versions have been released in the
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 32 @@@ 67 @@@ meantime fixing a large number of bugs and adding new functionality
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 33 @@@ 35 @@@ that may benefit your installation 
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 35 @@@ 62 @@@ the people involved with developing solr are also users of the
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 36 @@@ 70 @@@ software they are aware of the challenges involved in qualifying a new
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 37 @@@ 64 @@@ release before upgrading most of them are unwilling to upgrade a
train_2060.ann @@@ Body @@@ 38 @@@ 69 @@@ production install without first trying the new version out in an dev

train_3187.ann @@@ Body @@@ 26 @@@ 83 @@@ the current code is more optimized for finding the top k buckets from a total of n 
train_3187.ann @@@ Body @@@ 27 @@@ 90 @@@ when one asks to return the top 10 buckets when there are potentially millions of buckets 
train_3187.ann @@@ Body @@@ 28 @@@ 92 @@@ it makes sense to defer calculating other metrics for those buckets until we know which ones
train_3187.ann @@@ Body @@@ 29 @@@ 89 @@@ they are after we identify the top 10 buckets we calculate the domain for that bucket and
train_3187.ann @@@ Body @@@ 30 @@@ 44 @@@ use that to calculate the remaining metrics 
train_3187.ann @@@ Body @@@ 32 @@@ 66 @@@ the current method is obviously much slower when one is requesting
train_3187.ann @@@ Body @@@ 33 @@@ 86 @@@  all buckets we might as well just calculate all metrics in the first pass rather than
train_3187.ann @@@ Body @@@ 34 @@@ 21 @@@ trying to defer them 
train_3187.ann @@@ Body @@@ 36 @@@ 89 @@@ this inefficiency is compounded by the fact that the fields are not indexed in the second
train_3187.ann @@@ Body @@@ 37 @@@ 86 @@@ phase finding the domain for a bucket is a field query for an indexed field this would
train_3187.ann @@@ Body @@@ 38 @@@ 90 @@@ involve a single term lookup for a non indexed docvalues field this involves a full column
train_3187.ann @@@ Body @@@ 39 @@@ 5 @@@ scan

train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 49 @@@ 11 @@@  expression

train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 51 @@@ 6 @@@  fine 
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 53 @@@ 46 @@@  here are some thoughts on what you described 
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 55 @@@ 69 @@@  1 if you are closing the parallel stream after the top 1000 results 
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 56 @@@ 5 @@@  then
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 57 @@@ 70 @@@  try wrapping the intersect in a limitstream this stream doesn t exist
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 58 @@@ 4 @@@  yet
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 59 @@@ 71 @@@  so it will be a custom stream the limitstream can return the eof tuple
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 60 @@@ 70 @@@  after it reads n tuples this will cause the worker nodes to close the
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 61 @@@ 70 @@@  underlying stream and cause the broken pipe exception to occur at the
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 62 @@@ 43 @@@  export handler which will stop the export 
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 64 @@@ 28 @@@  here is the basic approach 
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 66 @@@ 40 @@@  parallel limit intersect search search 
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 69 @@@ 70 @@@  2 it can be tricky to understand where the bottleneck lies when using
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 70 @@@ 4 @@@  the
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 71 @@@ 63 @@@  parallelstream for parallel relational algebra you can use the
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 72 @@@ 11 @@@  nullstream
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 73 @@@ 70 @@@  to get an understanding of why performance is not increasing when you
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 74 @@@ 49 @@@  increase the workers here is the basic approach 
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 76 @@@ 39 @@@  parallel null intersect search search 
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 78 @@@ 74 @@@  the nullstream will eat all the tuples on the workers and return a single
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 79 @@@ 71 @@@  tuple with the tuple count and the time taken to run the expression so
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 80 @@@ 73 @@@  you ll get one tuple from each worker this will eliminate any bottleneck
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 81 @@@ 72 @@@  on tuples returning through the parallelstream and you can focus on the
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 82 @@@ 53 @@@  performance of the intersect and the export handler 
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 84 @@@ 22 @@@  then experiment with 
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 86 @@@ 45 @@@  1 increasing the number of parallel workers 
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 87 @@@ 61 @@@  2 increasing the number of replicas in the data collections 
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 89 @@@ 73 @@@  and watch the timing information coming back from the nullstream tuples 
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 90 @@@ 3 @@@  if
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 91 @@@ 72 @@@  increasing the workers is not improving performance then the bottleneck
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 92 @@@ 4 @@@  may
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 93 @@@ 68 @@@  be in the export handler so try increasing replicas and see if that
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 94 @@@ 72 @@@  improves performance different partitions of the streams will be served
train_3371.ann @@@ Body @@@ 95 @@@ 3 @@@  by

train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 86 @@@ 66 @@@  i think you ve got an incorrect idea of how java memory works you
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 87 @@@ 68 @@@  indicated that the heap stays stable at about 1 6gb but this is not
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 88 @@@ 70 @@@  how java works when a piece of memory is allocated by a java program 
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 89 @@@ 66 @@@  that memory is not reclaimed when the program no longer needs the
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 90 @@@ 68 @@@  object it is garbage collection a background process that frees the
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 91 @@@ 70 @@@  memory a graph of memory usage from a healthy java program looks like
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 92 @@@ 64 @@@  a sawblade allocations use up all the memory in one of the heap
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 93 @@@ 67 @@@  regions then garbage collection kicks in and frees up what it can 
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 94 @@@ 64 @@@  java s normal operation involves constant spikes in heap usage 
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 96 @@@ 72 @@@  the heap usage of solr will constantly increase as it runs then garbage
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 97 @@@ 71 @@@  collection will kick in when one of the heap regions reaches capacity 
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 98 @@@ 75 @@@  reclaiming objects that the program no longer needs and freeing up memory 
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 100 @@@ 73 @@@  oom happens when garbage collection is unable to free any memory because
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 101 @@@ 66 @@@  all of it is still in use there are exactly two ways to deal with
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 102 @@@ 65 @@@  oom 1 increase the size of your heap 2 make the program use less
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 103 @@@ 8 @@@  memory 
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 105 @@@ 69 @@@  i have two theories about why your solr install is using up all your
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 106 @@@ 68 @@@  heap and still requesting more 1 your solr caches particularly your
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 107 @@@ 67 @@@  filtercache may be very large 2 you may be doing a large number of
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 108 @@@ 68 @@@  queries that use a lot of memory a lot of facets and or using a lot
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 109 @@@ 33 @@@  of different fields for sorting 
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 111 @@@ 72 @@@  assuming the entire index is on one server for your 72 million document
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 112 @@@ 68 @@@  index each filtercache entry is 9 million bytes in size for your 28
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 113 @@@ 68 @@@  million document index each filtercache entry is 3 5 million bytes 
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 114 @@@ 71 @@@  the default size for the filtercache in solr example configs is 512 if
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 115 @@@ 72 @@@  you actually fill that cache up on a 72 million document index just the
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 116 @@@ 66 @@@  one cache would require more than the 4gb of memory that you have
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 117 @@@ 64 @@@  allocated to java you probably need to decrease the size of the
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 118 @@@ 13 @@@  filtercache 
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 120 @@@ 72 @@@  if you re doing a lot of facets or sorting you may need to increase the
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 121 @@@ 11 @@@  heap size 
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 123 @@@ 70 @@@  segment merges do use additional memory but i wouldn t expect that to
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 124 @@@ 57 @@@  be anything more than a minor contributor to heap usage 
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 126 @@@ 71 @@@  here s some additional reading on the subject of solr performance most
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 127 @@@ 71 @@@  of this page talks about memory because that s the limiting factor for
train_344.ann @@@ Body @@@ 128 @@@ 67 @@@  performance in most cases the page includes some information about
